File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function jacobi_am u m

 -- Function: jacobi_am (U, M)
     The Jacobi amplitude function, ‘jacobi_am’, is defined implicitly
     by (see http://functions.wolfram.com/09.24.02.0001.01) z = {\rm
     am}(w, m) where w = F(z,m) where F(z,m) is the incomplete elliptic
     integral of the first kind (‘elliptic_005ff’).  It is defined for
     all real and complex values of z and m.  In particular for real z
     and m with |m|<1, {\rm am}(z,m) maps the entire real line to the
     entire real line.  For other values of z and m, the following
     relationship is used: {\rm am}(z,m) = \sin^{-1}({\rm jacobi\_sn}(z,
     m)).

     Some examples:

     maxima
     
     (%i1) jacobi_am(z,0);
     (%o1)                           z
     
     
     (%i2) jacobi_am(z,1);
                                      z    %pi
     (%o2)                   2 atan(%e ) - ---
                                            2
     
     
     (%i3) jacobi_am(0,m);
     (%o3)                           0
     
     
     (%i4) jacobi_am(100, .5);
     (%o4)                   84.70311272411382
     
     
     (%i5) jacobi_am(0.5, 1.5);
     (%o5)                  0.4707197897046991
     
     
     (%i6) jacobi_am(1.5b0, 1.5b0+%i);
     (%o6)    9.340542168700782b-1 - 3.723960452146071b-1 %i

     maxima
     
     (%i1) plot2d([jacobi_am(x,.4),jacobi_am(x,.7),jacobi_am(x,.99),jacobi_am(x,.999999)],[x,0,10*%pi]);
     (%o1)                         false

     Compare this plot with the plot from
     https://dlmf.nist.gov/22.16.ivDLMF 22.16.iv:

␀[image src="figures/jacobi_am.png" alt="jacobi_am"␀]


     jacobi_am
     See also: ‘jacobi_am’, ‘elliptic_f’.


